Guidance has been provided to people on how to search for their family histories.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2010</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>5CE8530E-67D9-4746-9DE8-76C6148FC32A</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Cultural</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:sector>Leisure Activities, including Sports, Recreation and Tourism,Other</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The project has studied the history of marriage in Ireland 1660-1925. It has uncovered the various laws relating to marriage and made them clear. It has explored marital relationships, marital violence, desertion and divorce. It is the first study to explore the history of couple beggars in Ireland. The research adds considerably to our knowledge of sexual attitudes and practices in Ireland during the period and uncovers a wealth of detail about seduction, breach of promise to marry cases, bigamy and adultery, subjects that have not previously been explored to any extent in Irish history. The forthcoming book from Cambridge UNiversity Press will bring all of this information and analysis to public light.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Once the book is published it will open the way for further exploration on interpersonal relationships in Irish society, the power of the Churches in shaping people's private lives, and the relationships among the law, individuals, class and gender in Irish society.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>4D904A84-0ADF-4DE6-B418-F9D294FB5D75</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Other</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/799A6A25-56E7-41FA-94C